 Here's a function in JavaScript that takes an array of five numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a valid prime number. If it is, the function prints the prime number to the console:

```javascript
function findPrimeNumber(arr) {
  for (let num of arr) {
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(num);
      return;
    }
  }
}

function isPrime(n) {
  if (n <= 1) {
    return false;
  }
  for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(n); i++) {
    if (n % i === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}
```

The `findPrimeNumber` function loops through each number in the input array and calls the `isPrime` function to check if it's a prime number. If it is, the function prints the number to the console and returns. If none of the numbers in the array are prime, the function does not return anything.

